1. One friend is enough

4. Even good fortune leads eventually to death
5. Sex is a microcosm of life, transient joy then over.

author: Peter F. Hamilton
review content:
Mysterious magic
of an ancient
ethereous practice
Born under alien skies
Worlds beyond our own
Belonging to Stars,
now gone,
for eons...

Leave it
to Man
to ignore the locks
Hoping
to open
Pandora's box.

Hunger of men
to know
the wonder within
Becomes
Innocence's end
#MadVerse

author: Heather Gudenkauf
review content: At 18, I entered Notre Dame with my Grandmother in the early AM silence. I remember the weight of history & tears in her eyes as she lit a candle for my Grandfather.  To lose a place of peace is always a tragedy. At this time in our world, the loss is felt even more keenly.

author: Heather Gudenkauf
review content: Sometimes (most of the time.) the weight of hating myself is so much it feels like I can’t breathe and I have almost no friends so I just sit here in silence and suffer.

author: Heather Gudenkauf
review content:
For we have been socialized to respect fear more than our own needs for language and definition, and while we wait in silence for that final luxury of fearlessness, the weight of that silence will choke us. 
- AUDRE LORDE #MondayMotivation #MondayMorning

author: Heather Gudenkauf
review content:
What doesn't kill you
Makes you wish you were dead

And the weight of the world's getting harder to hold up

Would we be different
If we understood each other a little more?

author: Jalaluddin Rumi, Coleman Barks
review content:
Your hand opens and closes, opens and closes. If it were always a fist or always stretched open, you would be paralysed. Your deepest presence is in every small contracting and expanding, the two as beautifully balanced and coordinated as birds' wings.”
― Rumi, The Essential Rumi

review content:
“When you go through a hard period,
When everything seems to oppose you,
... When you feel you cannot even bear one more minute,
NEVER GIVE UP!
Because it is the time and place that the course will divert!” 
― Rumi, The Essential Rumi

author: Jalaluddin Rumi, Coleman Barks
review content:
Dear soul, if you were not friends with the vast nothing inside,
why would you always be casting your net into it,
and waiting so patiently?
.
This invisible ocean has given you such abundance,
but still you call it “death”,
~
[•Craftsmanship And Emptiness•]-The Essential Rumi

author: David Levithan
review content:
march 9

he was her friend — but it wasn't enough. love came between them, turned him into a lover. yet there's no perfect relationship. they broke up, and made each other, a stranger with memories.

f - friend
l - lover
s- stranger

even the dictionary got the order right.

author: David Levithan
review content:
Two lovers fall under a curse. They can only say a word once to each other. He used “love” on their third date. She said “everything” when they married. She’s dying now. He searches the dictionary for a word worthy of her.
“#Pulchritude.”
With her last breath “Felicitous.”#vss365

Best thing I heard all day.

author: Ruta Sepetys
review content: Stop saying there's plenty of fish in the sea when salt water fish are set to go extinct around 2048

author: Ruta Sepetys
review content: Finished Salt to the Sea today by @RutaSepetys and I'm both horrified but also educated about this dark time in history. I cared so much for these teens fate and her research to bring lost chapters together really made me feel so much! Don't sit on this book :)

author: Ruta Sepetys
review content:
The sea wove itself into my flesh
& I succumbed to its salt & sentience
reborn inside the blue temples
of beautifully haunting realms

small hands of tides reaching
in the language of fate
from shore to dusky shore
you transcended my dreams
one untameable beauty unbound.

#poetry

review content: In debates between anarchists and statists, the burden of proof clearly should rest on those who place their trust in the state. Anarchy’s mayhem is wholly conjectural; the state’s mayhem is undeniably, factually horrendous.

author: Scott Turow
review content:
Of course im not gonna change your mind, but the burden of proof is on the one making the accusations.
With such radical assumptions you must have some radical evidence, right?

author: Scott Turow
review content: Would you protect those you love? Or would you just stand idly by while they are murdered, raped or even tortured? You say that you stuffing God into these gaps of logic, 8s evidence? That is an assertion that carries a burden of proof!

author: Scott Turow
review content: And PLEASE, satisfy YOUR burden of proof without your argument from ignorance!

author: Scott Turow
review content: Burden of proof for what? There is no burden of proof on me to prove your claims and randomly quoting logical fallacies while proving you do not understand them doesnt make you look smart.

author: Scott Turow
review content: So show proof that it is what is claimed.  The burden of proof is on the person making the claim.

author: Scott Turow
review content: I don’t understand why consensual killing is a crime. I personally do not see why it is an offense if you have the boldness to do it. Burden of proof would be on the killer. Question is, how do you prove it was consensual and not malicious?

author: Scott Turow
review content: You are a disgusting human being, accusing people of heinous acts just because you're losing an argument. You're dumb . Btw look up burden of proof, if you make a claim the burden of proof is in you to back it up.

author: Scott Turow
review content: Please don't shift the burden of proof. You say he exists, you have to prove it. Thus the spider-man meme. Though you could just explain why He does the whole children with cancer thing? No matter which way I look at it, seems like a dick move.

author: Scott Turow
review content: That's not how the burden of proof works I'm afraid.

Endymion, and The Rise of Endymion are well worth a read, even though they don’t quite reach the level of the first two.

The Hyperion Cantos is a significant series in the sci-fi genre and remarkable even without the sci-fi epithet.

author: James Clavell
review content: Burning through The Asian Saga - onto Noble House

author: James Clavell
review content:
So I've followed up re-reading all the original PARKER novels by re-reading the James Clavell Asian Saga doorstop novels. 
TAI-PAN is even better than I remembered. 
NOBLE HOUSE is excellent so far (200 pages in; 1250 to go!).
But GAI-JIN? ZZzzzzzzzzzz....

author: James Clavell
review content: He was a Noble House (Asian Saga Book 5) and she was an Oriental Furniture Dragon Gong

author: James Clavell
review content: James Clavell's Asian Saga and Noble House Series are an absolute classic.

author: James Clavell
review content: Considering James Clavell's Asian Saga, Noble House is my favorite.

author: James Clavell
review content:
1905 would be able to bring in and update the Japanese and Russian stories mentioned in Gaijin and Noble House, plus changing the tone of the Asian Saga with Japan as a major power exerting political, economic & military pressure in the Asia-Pacific.

It could involve a Marlowe.

author: James Clavell
review content:
That would be absolutely incredible.

One major missed opportunity of the Asian Saga? Bartlett from Noble House and Corporal King from King Rat should have been the same person, and Marlowe reuniting with him in 1960s Hong Kong should have been a HUGE deal.

author: James Clavell
review content: I'm not anywhere near his level, but it was a daydream of mine once to be given permission to write more in his Asian Saga. Some of the stories mentioned in Noble House about Hag Straun during the Gilded Age are just crying out for a proper novel. Ah, well.

author: James Clavell
review content: Tai Pan was also awesome especially with Gildart Jackson's Scottish accents. Its story continues into Noble House which Ralph voices as well as Shogun. You would be doing yourself a disservice if you stopped the Asian saga at Shogun.

author: James Clavell
review content: Finished “Noble House” by James Clavell last night. Starting on “Shōgun” today. Hard to believe I have not read any of the epic novels in his Asian Saga before.

You know that scene with the two little girls in the Shining?

author: David Mitchell
review content:
Finished my first book for the #EndofYearathon, Slade House by David Mitchell. 

Has anyone else read this? I am. I don’t even know. This book was bizarre and it tricked me and it confused me, but I really liked it!

First time in a while I’ve stayed up late to finish a book.

author: David Mitchell
review content:

Nightmare Room, Slade House, & The Siren & The Specter--ing all, so far!
Also, I finished Widow's Point a few days ago & I already want to read it again!

titles: An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth
author: Chris Hadfield
review content: Now that I have a public Twtr account, and also because the holidays are here, I can't recommend "An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth" by @Cmdr_Hadfield more. I read it when I was 18 & it changed my life. I still reflect on many of the words in that book every day.

titles: An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth
author: Chris Hadfield
review content: Just finished reading @Cmdr_Hadfield ‘An Astronaut’s Guide to Life on Earth’! Incredible insight into space exploration & demonstrates a better way to live our lives; “Life is just a lot better if you feel you’re having 10 wins a day rather than a win every 10 years or so.”

titles: An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth
author: Chris Hadfield
review content: So last night, I finished @Cmdr_Hadfield's autobiography, "An Astronaut's Guide to Life On Earth" and wanted to take a minute to recommend it to all. Beyond the space dorkery I love, it has great lessons for leadership and for individuals who want to set and reach higher goals.

titles: An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth
author: Chris Hadfield
review content:
"Early success is a terrible teacher. You're essentially being rewarded for a lack of preparation, so when you find yourself in a situation where you must prepare. You can't do it, you don't know how"
-An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth

titles: An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth

In a meeting today, I politely but vehemently disagreed with the majority. I stood my ground and eventually we came to a great place.

The end.

review content:
Teringat lak poem time blaja menengah, 
"The Road Not Taken"
Two roads diverged in yellow wood,
And sorry i could not travel both,
And be one traveler long i stood,
And looked down one as far as i could,
To where it bent in the undergrowth;

Does the other road is any better...

author: Primo Levi, Stuart J. Woolf, Philip Roth
review content:
There were 3 roads for the Jewish people:

Mass Assimilation (voluntary genocide)
Bundism (a naive notion that burnt in Auschwitz)
Zionism (self determination)

The Jews opted for survival, for #Zionism. It is difficult to see how anti-Zionism is not an anti-Jewish position

author: Primo Levi, Stuart J. Woolf, Philip Roth
review content:
"We are slaves, deprived of every right, exposed to every insult, condemned to certain death, but we still possess one power, and we must defend it with all our strength for it is the last — the power to refuse our consent.” 
― Primo Levi, Survival in Auschwitz

author: Primo Levi, Stuart J. Woolf, Philip Roth
review content:
It might be Primo Levi’s book Survival in Auschwitz (If This Is a Man). Alongside Eli Wiesel’s Night, it is one of the most important books written by a survivor of Auschwitz-Birkenau.

In 1987 in his hometown of Turin, Italy, Primo Levi took his own life.

author: Primo Levi, Stuart J. Woolf, Philip Roth
review content:
You who live safe
In your warm houses, 
You who find warm food
And friendly faces when you return home. 
Consider if this is a man
Who works in mud, 
Who knows no peace, 
Who fights for a crust of bread, 
Who dies by a yes or no. P. LEVI, Survival in Auschwitz #synagogueshooting

author: Neil Gaiman, Marc Hempel, Richard Case, D'Israeli, Teddy Kristiansen, Glyn Dillon, Charles Vess, Dean Ormston, Kevin Nowlan, Todd Klein, Frank McConnell
review content:
“Have you ever been in love? Horrible isn't it? It makes you so vulnerable. It opens your chest and it opens up your heart and it means that someone can get inside you and mess you up.” 
― Neil Gaiman, The Sandman, Vol. 9: The Kindly Ones

author: Megan Whalen Turner
review content:
"King" is thrown around in this corner a lot.

Don't call me a king.

I'm no king. I'm no blue blood.

I don't want to be.

A modest proposal:

There has to be a DNP student somewhere who wants to look at all the intake questions nurses “have to” document, and figure out if they are based on :

2: science

Then we take all the EMR data we have and see which ones make a difference.

review content:
Of the 12 books I read in January, Maid by @stepville, On the Jellicoe Road by Melina Marchetta, and the Good Father by Noah Hawley are ones that I already know will stick with me the entire year and then some.

The bar is set high in 2019.

My father took one hundred and thirty-two minutes to die.

It happened on the Jellicoe Road. The prettiest road I’d ever seen, where trees made breezy canopies like a tunnel to Shangri-La.

author: Marcel Proust, Simon Vance, Lydia Davis
review content: Thus ends "Swann's Way', the first volume of Marcel Proust's seven volume novel "In Search of Lost Time" - (A la recherche de temps perdu). We will begin volume two, "Within a Budding Grove", after the Christmas break.

titles: Swann's Way (In Search of Lost Time, #1)
author: Marcel Proust, Simon Vance, Lydia Davis
review content: Nearing the end of Swann’s Way, the first volume of Proust’s “In Search of Lost Time” I can’t help thinking the whole work is like the Appalachian Trial, a pleasant, at times profoundly beautiful, but arduously long walk... I may not finish except for word nerd bragging rights.

titles: Swann's Way (In Search of Lost Time, #1)
author: Marcel Proust, Simon Vance, Lydia Davis
review content:
Custy: I need this book by Marcel Pr-ow-st. In Search of Lost Time.
Me, trying to be amicable: of course, are you looking for Swann’s Way? That’s the first one.
Custy, rolling eyes, clearly knows more: I don’t think you understand. I need in Search of Lost Time for a class.

review content: That's really interesting! I'm currently working on my own novel based on In Search of Lost Time, which is set in Chicago from 2007-2022. I love Proust because I found out in 2013 that my 20th birthday was the 100th Anniversary of Swann's Way's publication: November 14, 2013.

• "Missoula: Rape and the Justice System in a College Town" by Jon Krakauer (2015)
• "Homo Ludens: A Study of the Play Element in Culture" by Johan Huizinga (1938)

Missoula is far too timely in light of the recent national discourse on sexual assault.

Laying in bed naked, breathless and covered in salty sweat.

author: Maya Banks
review content:
we found ourselves 
breathless, facing the Sun 
crows preening wings 
on a wire 
a cold February morning 
it had been oddly warm 
the day before 
wild swings 
temperatures tease 
how easy it is to lull 
cabin fever crews 
wishing themselves 
further into Spring 
thought to naught

review content:
Most influential books read in my childhood: 
• The Bible (duh)
• "Oliver Twist" by Dickens
• "Selected Poems" by Eliot

• "My Name is Asher Lev" by Potok
• The Hardy Boys. All of 'em.
• "Brave New World" by Huxley
• "Wrinkle in Time" by L'Engle

author: Bill Watterson
review content: Gonna treat myself to the complete Calvin and Hobbes comic collection, since I used to collect the Sunday newspaper editions for about three years straight when I was a kid. Should I go paperback, or take the extra hit for hardcover?

author: Bill Watterson
review content: Yesterday, I was just a boy. Today, I am a man, a man who now owns the Calvin and Hobbes complete comic strip collection.

author: Bill Watterson
review content: I only bring out my Calvin and Hobbes complete collection set in the winter and refuse to do so any other time of the year

author: Bill Watterson
review content:
Doing Konmari and the burned stuff that didn't spark joy. Now all I have left is a shirt, two pajama pants and my complete collection of Calvin and Hobbes.

The coals of what was my apartment are cooling and I need shelter. What's the next step? I didn't actually read the book.

author: Bill Watterson
review content: Bill Watterson's introduction to The Complete Calvin and Hobbes is hands down one of my favorite pieces of writing, period. The way he explains his reasons not to license his comic strip characters' likenesses is so matter-of-fact . . . I'm in awe of his dedication to the craft.

author: Bill Watterson
review content: BOOK REVIEW: "The Complete Calvin and Hobbes" by Bill Watterson (2012) - There's a stretch of comics from about 1992 to 1994 that are extremely, extremely funny. Four stars.

author: Bill Watterson
review content: I just ordered the Calvin and Hobbes Complete set. There's never been a purchase where I have had more privilege, pride, and pure honour then the one that I have just made

author: Bill Watterson
review content:
A 20-lb package arrived for me in the mail—an early birthday gift. My landlord offered to drop it off at my apartment because it’s heavy. The package is the boxed set of the Complete Calvin and Hobbes. 

I’m such a big fan but I’m embarrassed to tell my landlord.

author: Bill Watterson
review content: This year we were blessed that Santa gave our family “The Complete Calvin And Hobbes” and tonight I got to share the first reading with my daughter, who had no previous idea what C&H meant to me, and the laughter I heard, I hope I never forget.

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: I very recently (finally) got around to reading the Culture series. Only one book left now, and I feel a little sad that onece that’s done there will be no more to discover. I have enjoyed this series a lot. Except for Use of Weapons, which can get in the bin.

author: Iain M. Banks
review content:
I'm finding Use Of Weapons - Culture Series book 3 to be a bit of a slog.

I can't quite keep up with the time frame hopping narrative. And the fact that every woman char gets a paragraph of description that includes her sexual desirability, is throwing me out of the immersion.

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: if I didn't care for Use of Weapons and hated Excession, what Culture novel should be my last attempt to get into the series?

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: Listening to the last Culture novel I haven't finished, 'Use of Weapons.' Zakalwe remains my least liked of Iain Banks' protagonists which is why I stopped reading it years ago. Odd how much easier it is to get through in audio format though.

author: Iain M. Banks
review content:
While I'm irritating people with my opinions, here's every Culture novel ranked:
1. Surface Detail (because hells)
2. Look To Windward (because dirigible behemothaur)
3. Player Of Games (because Azad)
4. Excession
5. Use Of Weapons
6. Consider Phlebas
7. Hydrogen Sonata
7. Matter

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: Still in Use of Weapons, obviously. Think I'll do Matter next. Love the Shell-World. And hey, another outsider from The Culture forced to deal with a drastic change in context!

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: The culture of violence is sustained through criminality (use of weapons, availability of firearms), inequality,poverty, unemployment, values related to violence and crime, vulnerability of young people & inappropriate youth socialization, substance abuse, male sexual entitlement

author: Iain M. Banks
review content:
ngl, I'm not into TV but I might be into Amazon Presents: The Culture: USE OF WEAPONS

but only if they don't tone it down

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: Should the Culture novels be properly read in publication order? I've read Phlebas and I'm finishing Player of Games; should I wait for Use of Weapons to arrive or could I skip to Excession? @pkincaid_critic?

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: I've always been uh caught I suppose between 'Use of Weapons' (slight Culture fan stereotype) and Excession tho it's prob Excession. 3rd is Matter though I always considered it a close contender. (All 3 personal pref not expertise in literature.)

author: Iain M. Banks
review content: After putting it down for many months, I finally finished Use Of Weapons and holy shit that ending. Honestly though, I would've liked it better if someone in The Culture straight up knew and the use of Zakalwe was more intentional. My fav in the series so far. On to Excession.

author: Margaret Atwood
review content:
I mean, personal rankings are personal, but: 
1) Cat's Eye (probably objectively her best)
2) The Robber Bride
3) Oryx and Crake (I don't know why, I just like Jimmy)

author: Adam Hochschild
review content: My 10 favourite books this year in no order: King Leopold’s Ghost by Adam Hochschild, a chilling, thorough account of Belgium’s brutal colonisation of The Congo

author: Adam Hochschild
review content:
If you haven't yet, please read King Leopold's Ghost.
It's a detailed analysis of the colonisation of Congo & how destructive & violent King Leopold & Belgium were. 
It's not a pleasant read, but important in understanding Congo's history & the continued effects of colonisation.

author: Adam Hochschild
review content:
Gotta write an essay about this, but if you're genuinely interested in learning about why African countries operate the way they do, I recommend:
-The Sacrifice of Africa (Katongole)
-The Locust Effect (Haugen & Boutros)
-King Leopold's Ghost (Hoschschild)

author: Laurelin Paige
review content:
Here's how Walmart cleverly extracts margin from its vendors:

1. They give you a giant order
2. You build high fixed cost infrastructure to support the volume
3. They tell you to reduce price or fuck off
4. You reduce price or take big losses on investment to support their scale

1/2

author: Cormac McCarthy
review content: All the Pretty Horses is a part of The Border Trilogy (along with The Crossing and Cities of the Plain).  The Road and Blood Meridian =great (and bleak) but Suttree seems to me his most overlooked.  And bonus, there's some humor in it.  Happy reading!

author: Cormac McCarthy
review content: I'm about to finish the last book in the "Border Trilogy" by Cormac McCarthy. The second in the trilogy, "The Crossing," is my favorite but they are all excellent. They offer a much needed perspective on our American idea of the "west" and just how intertwined it is with Mexico.

review content: Omg u need to read the border trilogy by mcarthy.  All the pretty horses, the crossing, and cities on the plain.  He is by far the best living author.

review content: Take a closer look at the spire that has collapsed and you might understand how much of history, art and culture has disappeared with it. Maybe not everyone will understand the meaning of what’s happening but this is truly an event that will mark history. #NotreDame #Parispic.twitter.com/Y6mnFKAbt9

author: H.W. Janson, Anthony F. Janson
review content: Why has the burning of Notre Dame moved so many? Because we believe in beauty, majesty, faith, art, history, and the human expressions thereof. We recognize in this cathedral our common humanity. A scar now emerges in our connections to our past, our future, and each other.

author: H.W. Janson, Anthony F. Janson
review content: Notre Dame de Paris is more than 800 years old. It took 200 years to build. 800 years of history, symbolism and art are burning in flames.  pic.twitter.com/iiWw8dizcz

author: H.W. Janson, Anthony F. Janson
review content: The beautiful Notre Dame Cathedral. The monument’s history, art, and iconic architecture is irreplaceable. The people of Paris, France, and Catholics around the world are in our prayers.#NotreDame (Photos by Oliver Wong)pic.twitter.com/DN7tKBLd3Q

author: H.W. Janson, Anthony F. Janson
review content:
The Notre dame, not only being the soul of Paris, speaks of human history and represents how we evolved with art, culture and religion alongside. It is in our hearts to mourn for such a terrible damage but it is also in our souls to rebuild and preserve these legacies.
#Notredamepic.twitter.com/82fTaXLdoY

author: H.W. Janson, Anthony F. Janson

review content:
Notre-Dame’s construction started in 1163 and it was opened in 1345 - it took almost 200 years to complete.

author: Frank McCourt
review content: It has been suggested (by those I respect) that it would be great to write my memoir around my life so far as a teacher. I think of Frank McCourt's teacher man but I wonder: how does one tell all the tales without poking the hornet's nest that is education politics. Advice sought

author: Frank McCourt
review content:
Two literary genres that I wish more people would read:
1. Plays (especially Pirandello, Albee, O'Neill, Shange, & Hansberry)
2. Memoirs (from Frank McCourt's Angela's Ashes, 'Tis, & Teacher Man, to Trevor Noah's Born a Crime)

Sadly, these genres are often skipped in college.

author: Frank McCourt
review content: I recommend “Teacher Man” because the reader experiences the development of Frank McCourt as an educator. “Teacher Man” has an array of students over his 30 years of teaching. The complex life events of fatherhood & love highlighted in the book showcase his reality. @TJAPEnglish

It is a crime, A CRIME, that most fans of Avatar The Last Airbender aren't aware that there are comics out there that depict the trials and adventures of the Gaang after the show.

I *highly* recommend "The Search". It details the origin and fate of Zuko's mother. 9/10.

author: Rob Sheffield
review content: While discussing Pete Shelley’s passing, my wife just reminded me that “Why Can’t I Touch It?” was on the first mix tape I made for her in 1986. This hits me the very week that I’m finally reading @robsheff’s lovely Love Is a Mix Tape, after years of intending to do so.

author: Rob Sheffield
review content: I started reading @robsheff “Love is a Mix Tape ...” based on a recommendation from @Harry_Styles - i can’t put it down. I didn’t realize Rob is just a few years older than me so the fact that he loves @Harry_Styles as much as me makes me more secure in my love for Harry.

author: Rob Sheffield
review content: in all the tears i’ve shed reading books none compare to the number of tears i cried reading @robsheff’s love is a mix tape

author: Rob Sheffield
review content: Oh my! Reading @robsheff's Love is a Mix Tape near Christmas-time / NYE is the best decision I've made this year. I'm having a good chuckle reading it. And a few good cries. And a few not-so-good cries.

author: Rob Sheffield
review content: Last night when I got to speak to some NYU students about music journalism, I got to tell them about how @robsheff and his writing are the reason why I started doing what I'm doing. I told the class they should all read Love Is A Mix Tape to inspire them too.

titles: The Things We Wish Were True
author: Marybeth Mayhew Whalen
review content: history has told us that we must conform to whiteness in order to succeed in a world not designed for non-whites. To the extent of which that may be true, never lose sight of your culture and where you came from. I wish things weren’t the way they were

titles: The Things We Wish Were True
author: Marybeth Mayhew Whalen
review content: Happy Thanksgiving fam.  Sorry we have been absent for so long.  I wish things were different right now as we miss you all but thank you all to our loyal supporters through this.  More importantly thank you all so much for the true friendship with each and everyone of you.

titles: The Things We Wish Were True
author: Marybeth Mayhew Whalen
review content:
1. We can't sustain this behavior, blaming an entire group for the acts of a few or an individual. It's wrong.

2. The Media needs to remember it's job is to report the Facts, not rumors, not things they wish were true. 

These two things would help a ton in ending division.

titles: The Things We Wish Were True
author: Marybeth Mayhew Whalen
review content: I wish I was still in Hype man. The things that we used to talk about and work on were honestly the best times I had gaming wise. Happy for what they're doing now tho, just sucks I couldn't be apart of seeing the things that we talked about come true.

titles: The Things We Wish Were True

review content: I wish psychology article introductions were just: “Most of the published literature is probably useless. There’s these two general things that seem pretty true. What if we put them together for a study? Here’s what we did...”

titles: The Things We Wish Were True
author: Marybeth Mayhew Whalen
review content: Sometimes I wish that things could go back to the way they were, but then I remember that God has a plan for me and that everything He does happens for true reason. It hurts sometimes but He puts us through things to make us stronger and wiser than we were before.

titles: The Things We Wish Were True

review content: People find regrets in messing things up and making something that they wish they could take back. Those shouldn’t be regrets those should be life lessons. True regrets in life are the times where we didn’t chase our desires or take the opportunities that we were given

titles: The Things We Wish Were True

titles: The Things We Wish Were True
author: Marybeth Mayhew Whalen
review content: I hate how I always realize the true value of things only once I've lost them, but I'm thankful that I had even gotten the chance to be your friend and that we were able to share memories together, in this lifetime. I wish I was able to tell you that myself. RIP, Our Brother.

titles: The Things We Wish Were True

review content: I get joules from dead people, from the attention and love they receive, maybe they also wish that they received it earlier when they were alive, but we realise the true values of things when it's already too late.
